Project 1¶

Chandler Ellsworth and Kelley Breeze¶

Overall Goal¶

  • Write functions that will manipulate and process data sets that come in a certain form
  • Create and fit basic linear regression models
  • Create a cross-validation function to judge the models

The purpose of this project is to provide a guide as to how to read in and process data in python as well as create, test and judge linear models. We will also see how to create our own functions that can do these steps for us for similar data sets.

Throughout the project we will be working with data in the form of .csv files from the Census Bureau. The first two data sets contain information about public school enrollment. The last four data sets have information about resident population estimates, and will be used for double checking that our combine_dataframes() function generalizes for other census data sets. All of the data sets have the same general format, which will allow us to create functions that can streamline our workflow when reading in, parsing, and combining this data.

We will be breaking down the work into distinct steps to make things clear. First, we will begin by reading in and parsing the first education data set (https://www4.stat.ncsu.edu/~online/datasets/EDU01a.csv) in our Data Processing section. In the Writing Functions to Help with Data Processing section we will write our own functions that can accomplish what we achieved in the Data Processing steps, and use these functions to neatly read in and parse the second education data set (https://www4.stat.ncsu.edu/~online/datasets/EDU01b.csv). In the Call It and Combine Our Data section we will use the wrapper() function that we created to read in and parse our two .csv files that we have been working with and then combine them into a single object (a list with two data frames, one for county data and the other for non-county data) using our combine_dataframes() function. In the Cross-Validation section we will create a simple linear regression model and a multiple linear regression model for our non-county data, and evaluate them based on a cross-validation function that we will create.

Before getting started we will import the modules and functions that we will need to run our analyses.

Data Processing Step 2: Converting from Wide to Long Format using the melt() funtion from pandas¶

Our next step is to convert our data from wide format, where we have multiple observations in a given row, to long format, where we will only have one observation per row. Long format data is much more useful when we want to run statistical analysis, so we want to convert from wide to long format before going any further. The censusdata data frame has many columns that end in D, that are all based on different observations in a given year.

The melt() function will allow us to take the enrollment values (values stored in columns ending in "D") and create a new data frame with just one observation perenrollment value for each area_name. This will create two new columns in our data frame. The new survey column will have the names of the columns that ended in D from the previous data frame, and the enrollment column will contain the actual number of enrolled based on the survey type. We will store our new data frame as datamelt.

In [6]:
datamelt = censusdata.melt(id_vars = ['area_name', 'STCOU'], var_name = 'survey', value_name = 'enrollment')

Data Processing Step 3: Parsing Our survey Column to Create a 4 Digit year Variable and a measurement Variable¶

Now that our data is in long format, let's pulll some additional information from our survey variable to make things more easy to understand. The coded information in our survey column gives information about the year that data was collected in addition to the survey type used. We want to get this information and create two new variables, year and measurement, before moving on in our data processing.

We can use a for loop to iterate over the rows of our datamelt data frame to create our new year and measurement variables. The for loop will iterate over the values in the survey column. The survey values are all in the same format, with the first three characters of the column representing the survey type (in this case all surveys are EDU), the next four characters represent the type of value you have from that survey, and the last two characters prior to the D represent the year of the measurement.

Before the loop we will initialize two empty lists, year and measurement. These will allow us to build our year and measurement columns (both list objects within the loop) using the .append() method.

Within the loop we will create three variables:

  • The check variable will identify index 7 of the string for that observation in the survey column. This will be used to determine if a 19 or a 20 should be created for the first two digits of the year variable.
  • The shortmeasurement variable for each value will slice the survey string to return values from index 0 to 6 in order to create our new measurement variable.
  • The shortyear variable will help in creating the new year variable for every observation in our data set. The loop will add a 20 in front of shortyear if the 7th index value of the survey string is less than 2 (that is, if check is less than 2), and add a 19 in front of shortyear for any check that is not less than 2.

Each iteration of the loop will add values to the year and measurement lists. Finally, we will add the year and measurment lists to our dataframe, and use the .drop() method to remove the old survey column. We will store the resulting pandas DataFrame as an object called cleandatamelt.

In [7]:
year = []
measurement = []
for x in datamelt['survey']:
    check = x[7]
    shortyear = x[7:9]
    shortmeasurement = x[:7]
    if int(check) < 2:
        year.append(int('20' + shortyear))
        measurement.append(shortmeasurement)
    else:
        year.append(int('19' + shortyear))
        measurement.append(shortmeasurement)

datamelt['year'] = year
datamelt['measurement'] = measurement
cleandatamelt = datamelt.drop(columns = 'survey')

Data Processing Step 4: Split the Data into Two Data Frames (non_county and county) Based on area_name¶

We now want to create two separate data frames from our cleandatamelt object, one for county level data and another for non-county level data. We will use the .apply() method with a lambda function to create an indexing vector that we can use to do the subsetting. Note that for all non-county level area_names the -4 index will not contain a ,, while all county level data will contain a , at the -4 index. This will allow us to use the logical_not() function from numpy to limit our returned values to only those that do not include county information for our non_county data set, and only those that contain county level data for our county dataset. We also need to include copy() to ensure that we are making a copy of the data sets and not merely creating views. We will store these as data frames called non_county and county.

Data Processing Step 6: Creating a New Variable for division in Our non_county Data Frame¶

Creating get_division() Helper Function¶

The get_division() helper function will take in a state name string and return the correct division (in the form of a string) where the state belongs. If a non-state is entered the get_division() function will return an error. We will use this helper function in the next section where we create our own functions to carry out data processing on similar data frames.

In [11]:
def get_division(x):
    """
    Take in a state name string and return the correct division.
    """
    if x in ['CONNECTICUT', 'MAINE', 'MASSACHUSETTS', 'NEW HAMPSHIRE', 'RHODE ISLAND', 'VERMONT']:
        return 'Division_1'
    elif x in ['NEW JERSEY', 'NEW YORK', 'PENNSYLVANIA']:
        return 'Division_2'
    elif x in ['ILLINOIS', 'INDIANA', 'MICHIGAN', 'OHIO', 'WISCONSIN']:
        return 'Division_3'
    elif x in ['IOWA', 'KANSAS', 'MINNESOTA', 'MISSOURI', 'NEBRASKA', 'NORTH DAKOTA', 'SOUTH DAKOTA']:
        return 'Division_4'
    elif x in ['DELAWARE', 'FLORIDA', 'GEORGIA', 'MARYLAND', 'NORTH CAROLINA', 'SOUTH CAROLINA', 'VIRGINIA', 'WEST VIRGINIA']:
        return 'Division_5'
    elif x in ['ALABAMA', 'KENTUCKY', 'MISSISSIPPI', 'TENNESSEE']:
        return 'Division_6'
    elif x in ['ARKANSAS', 'LOUISIANA', 'OKLAHOMA', 'TEXAS']:
        return 'Division_7'
    elif x in ['ARIZONA', 'COLORADO', 'IDAHO', 'MONTANA', 'NEVADA', 'NEW MEXICO', 'UTAH', 'WYOMING']:
        return 'Division_8'
    elif x in ['ALASKA', 'CALIFORNIA', 'HAWAII', 'OREGON', 'WASHINGTON']:
        return 'Division_9'
    else:
        return 'ERROR'

Using get_division() Helper Function and np.vectorize() Function to Create a New division Variable¶

The vectorize() function is used to create a vectorized function. We first want to define our vecotized function (in this case we want to vectorize our get_division() helper function) and store this as a vectorized function called div_vectorize(). We will then call the div_vectorize() function using the area_name column from our non_county data set. This will carryout the get_division() function on the entire area_name column and allow us to create our new division variable.

Part 2: Writing Functions to Help with Data Processing¶

The filter_data() Function¶

The filter_data() function will combine data processing steps one and two from above. This function will select the columns Area_name, STCOU, and all columns ending in D from the data frame supplied, x, with the help of .loc[] and .str.endswith(). It will then convert this from wide format to long format using the .melt() method from pandas. The funtion will return our filtered data frame in long format. This function has an optional argument, values_name=, that gives users the option to specify the name of the column representing the value.

NOTE: To make this function more able to generalize to other census datasets we have set the default for the values_name= argument to count. This allows for modification based on the census data set being analyzed, where a more descriptive name for this variable might be desired. The census education data sets are measuring enrollment numbers, and so when we read those in we will change the argument to values_name=enrollment. For other datasets we will use the default value of this argument, count, when reading in the data.

In [14]:
def filter_data(x, values_name = 'count'):
    """
    Rename 'Area_name', select relevant columns, and convert wide format to long format.
    """
    x.rename(columns = {'Area_name' : 'area_name'}, inplace = True)
    clean_data = x.loc[:, x.columns.str.endswith(('D', 'area_name', 'STCOU'))]
    data_melt = clean_data.melt(id_vars = ['area_name', 'STCOU'], var_name = 'survey', value_name = values_name)
    return data_melt

The survey_parse() Function¶

The survey_parse() function will carry out data processing step 3, taking in a data frame (the output from our filter_data() function) and creating new variables for year and measurement based on the survey column. The survey_parse() function then drops the survey column from our data set. This function returns a data frame containing our new variables.

In [15]:
def survey_parse(x):
    """
    Takes in a pandas data frame and creates 'new year' and 'measurement' columns by parsing through the 'survey' column and then dropping the 'survey' column.
    """
    survey_year = []
    survey_measurement = []
    for i in x['survey']:
        check_ = i[7]
        short_year = i[7:9]
        short_measurement = i[:7]
        if int(check_) < 2:
            survey_year.append(int('20' + short_year))
            survey_measurement.append(short_measurement)
        else:
            survey_year.append(int('19' + short_year))
            survey_measurement.append(short_measurement)

    x['year'] = survey_year
    x['measurement'] = survey_measurement
    clean_data_melt = x.drop(columns = 'survey')
    return clean_data_melt

The get_state() Function¶

The get_state() function will be used to help parse the area_name variable in our county data frame and create a new variable corresponding to the state indicated in the area_name of the dataframe. For all area_names in the county data frame the two letter state abbreviation is at the end of the string. As a result, we can access the state from the area_name using negative indexing x[-2:].

In [16]:
def get_state(x):
    """
    Adds a 'state' column to pandas data frame based on last two elements of 'area_name' string. 
    """
    x['state'] = x['area_name'].apply(lambda x : x[-2:])

The add_division Function¶

We will create the add_division() function next to iterate over the area_name for our data and return a division variable that will be added to our data frame. The add_division() function takes advantage of the get_division() helper function created earlier. We will again be using np.vectorize() to create a verctorized version of the get_division() helper function.

In [17]:
def add_division(x):
    """
    Uses the get_division() helper function to iterate over 'area_name' in pandas data frame to create a new 'division' column.
    """
    div_vectorize = np.vectorize(get_division)
    x['division'] = div_vectorize(x['area_name'])

The split_df() Function¶

The split_df() function takes in a data frame (the output of the survey_parse() function) and returns a list containing two data frames, one for county data and another for non_county data, as in data processing step 4 above. It also relies on the get_state() function to generate a state name variable for our county data frame, and the add_division() function to create a division variable for our non_county data frame.

In [18]:
def split_df(x):
    """
    Create two separate data frames as copies of inputted data frame based on county and non-county rows.
    Uses get_state() and add_division() helper functions to create appropriate state and division columns.
    """
    non_county_data = x.loc[x['area_name'].apply(lambda x : np.logical_not(x[-4] == ',')),:].copy()
    county_data = x.loc[x['area_name'].apply(lambda x : np.logical_not(x[-4] != ',')),:].copy()
    get_state(county_data)
    add_division(non_county_data)
    return [county_data, non_county_data]

The wrapper() Function to Do It All in One Step!¶

The wrapper() function will take in the URL of a .csv file in this format, and the optional argument for the variable name, call all of the functions above, and return the two data frames in a list. As with the filter_data() function above, the default value for the values_name= argument is count to allow this variable to apply more generally to other census data sets. When we call this function for our education data sets we will change from the default argument to values_name=enrollment.

In [19]:
def wrapper(link, values_name = 'count'):
    """
    Reads a csv file from a URL with an optional values_name argument and calls all helper functions to return a list of county and non_county dataframes.
    """
    census_data = pd.read_csv(link)
    return split_df(survey_parse(filter_data(census_data, values_name)))

We will use our wrapper() function to read in and parse the two .csv files containing education data from the census bureau. We will store these data frames as edu1 and edu2.

The combine_dataframes() Function¶

The combine_dataframes() function will join our county level data sets together and our state level data sets together. The * allows our combine_dataframe() function to take unlimited positional arguments for census_dataframe, allowing us to combine more than 2 data frames at a time. The combine_dataframes() function will return a list containing two elements, a data frame for all county level data (merged from all the census_dataframes input to the function) and a dataframe for non-county data, again from the combined data sets.

NOTE: The data frames provided to the combine_dataframes function should all have the same name for the values_name = argument used with the wrapper() function from when we read in the data.

In [21]:
def combine_dataframes(*census_dataframe):
    """
    Takes in lists of county and non_county data frames outputted from the wrapper function and returns a new list, joining together
    the county level data sets and non_county level data sets. 
    """
    county_list = list(map(lambda x : x[0], census_dataframe))
    county_merge = reduce(lambda x, y : pd.concat([x, y]), county_list)
    non_county_list = list(map(lambda x : x[1], census_dataframe))
    non_county_merge = reduce(lambda x, y : pd.concat([x, y]), non_county_list)
    return [county_merge, non_county_merge]

Calling the combine_dataframes() Function to Combine Our edu1 and edu2 Data Frames¶

We will use the combine_dataframes() function to combine our data sets and then split into two separate data frames, one for county data and another for non_county data. We will store the returned list as census_combined_list for use in part 4, where we will build and test two linear models.

Double Check That It Generalizes!¶

We will now check that our combine_dataframes() function generalizes by reading in four census data sets containing resident total population estimates. Note that our wrapper() function has a default of values_name = 'count', which we will use for all four data sets to ensure that all data sets read in will have the same variable name for this new variable.

Creating a cross_validation() Function¶

We want to see how well our SLR_model and MLR_model predict our enrollment values. Because our data is over time we will want to create a function to train the model and judge sequantially by year.

The get_MSE() Helper Function¶

The get_MSE function will take in a dataframe of predictors (X), a 1D response (y), and a last_year argument. The get_MSE() function will raise an error if the last_year entered is greater than 2005, as the education data set only contains years 1987-2006 and the last test set generated will contain information from 2006 (equivalent to last_year + 1).

We will need to import the mean_squared_error() function from sklearn.metrics to help in our get_MSE() function. Note that we imported all required packages and functions at the beginning, so we will not repeat it here. The code import this function is:

    from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error

To create our training set we will include all years up to and including the last_year. The test set will only include the last_year + 1, or the year after the last_year entered. As there are many steps within the get_MSE() function, we have provided additional commented notes within the code block for clarity.

In [33]:
def get_MSE(X, Y, last_year):
    """
    Returns the MSE by joining a data frame of predictors and 1D response.
    Creates a training set based on the years prior to, and including, the 'last_year' specified.
    Creates a test set based on the year after the 'last_year' specified.
    """
    if last_year > 2005:
        raise Exception("The last year cannot be greater than 2005!")
    # Creating training and test sets 
    data_set = pd.concat([X, Y], axis=1)# Creating a dataset combining the X and Y data frames provided by the user.
    training_set = data_set.loc[data_set['year'] < (last_year + 1)]# Creating our training set 
    test_set = data_set.loc[data_set['year'] == last_year + 1]# Creating our test set

    # Creating our linear regression model
    reg = linear_model.LinearRegression()
    reg.fit(training_set.iloc[:, :-1], training_set['enrollment'].values)
    
    # Creating predictions for our test_set based on our model (reg)
    pred1 = reg.predict(test_set.iloc[:, :-1])

    # Getting MSE from our test_set using the true enrollment values from test_set and the predicted y values from our model
    MSE = mean_squared_error(y_true = test_set['enrollment'], y_pred = pred1)
    return(MSE)

Creating our predictor and response dataframes for the get_MSE() function¶

We need to create our data frames for the get_MSE() function. For the SLR model we will only have one predictor variable year. The MLR model will have two predictor variables, year and division. We will create our X predictor data frames using .loc[] to subset our cv_subset data frame by our predictor variables. We will store the predictors for the SLR model as SLR_X_predictors and the predictor data frame for our MLR model as MLR_X_predictors. We will create a 1D response, a pandas series called response_Y, by subsetting the cv_subset data frame by enrollment.

The cv_error() Function¶

This data set is based on enrollment values over time, and so the traditional train vs test set approach or built-in cross validation functions will not be appropriate because we need to account for the year when creating these groups, and not simply randomly split our data into training or test sets, or k-folds in cross-validation. We will need to write a function to train our models and judge them sequentially.

The cv_error() function will obtain the CV value over all the years (other than the initial training block of the first three years of data). The cv-error() function will handle this for us by taking data from the first three years (acting as a training set) and using that to predict the enrollment for the fourth year (acting as our test set). It will then use the get_MSE() helper function to generate an MSE value for this "test set" based on the model created by the "training set". The cv_error() function will then move on to the next fold, and use the first four years to predict the fifth year, calculate the MSE for the predictions, and add this MSE to the MSE value from the first iteration of the loop using augmented assignment. It will continue in this manner until it reaches the last year of the data set. The cv_error() function will return the summed MSE values to give us the overall MSE for the model.

In [37]:
def cv_error(X, Y, first_year):
    """
    Returns the summed MSE values by iterating through the values between 
    the 'first_year' specified and the last year in the 'year' column of the 
    data frame, so long as the year is not less than 1989.
    The MSE for each year is found using the get_MSE() helper function. 
    """
    if first_year < 1989:
        raise Exception("The first year must be greater than 1989!")
    
    MSE = 0

    for i in range(first_year, X['year'].max()):
        yearly_MSE = get_MSE(X, Y, i)
        MSE += yearly_MSE
    return MSE

Part 6: Comparing Models Using MSE¶

SLR Model MSE¶

In [38]:
SLR_Model_MSE = cv_error(SLR_X_predictors, response_Y, 1989)
print(f'SLR Model MSE is: {SLR_Model_MSE}')

SLR Model MSE is: 17529166024130.021

We can see that the MSE for our SLR model was 17529166024130.021. This value represents mean squared difference between the actual values for enrollment and the predicted values for enrollment calculated for each year in our data set, other than the initial three year training block of years 1987-1989, and then summed to genreate a total model MSE by the cv_error() function.

The SLR model had a single predictor, year, to predict enrollment. As there is only one predictor in our model, year, each data point within a given year will have the same predicted enrollment value. This means that if there is a lot of variation in the data within each year in terms of enrollment that most data points will fall far from the fitted line of our model, and therefore generate larger MSE values. Additionally, the enrollment values themselves are large numbers, often in the hundreds of thousands to millions, and this would also contribute to a large MSE value, particularly when considering that MSE is a mean squared distance from the regression line for a given year's enrollment numbers.

The MSE value for the SLR Model are large, so let's take a look at some information about these variables in our original data set to see if this is reasonable based on the data. First, let's look at a scatterplot of year and enrollment to see if we can see any clear patterns. We will use the regplot() function from seaborn to create a scatterplot with a regression line.

We can see that for 1990 we have enrollment values ranging from a minimum of 94,776, to a maximum of 4,771,978 with a mean of 813,125.98. This high level of variation for enrollment variables that are also quite large would lead to high MSE values. Taken alone, the MSE value does not mean much, but we can use it to compare two different models based on the same data set and response variable.

Comparing SLR Model to MLR Model¶

In comparing the two models created to predict the same response variable, we want to select the model with a lower MSE, as this would indicate overall predicted observations from the model closer to the true values from our test set. In this analysis, the MLR model overall MSE is 4,441,848,846,720.795 lower than the SLR model overall MSE and is the preferred model for predicting enrollment, especially considering the MLR used is easily interpretable.

As discussed previously, the large MSE values here are expected as there is a lot of variation in enrollment within subgroups of our data (within the year for the SLR model and within the year by division subgroup for the MLR model) and the enrollment values themselves are quites large, often in the hundreds of thousands. The cv_error() function is also calculating the overall MSE by summing together MSE values for each sequential year, with separate test sets from 1990 to 2006, futher increasing the resulting total model MSE values that are returned.

MSE vs RMSE¶

MSE is measured in squared units. The RMSE is the square root of the MSE and can be more easy to interpret as it is in the same units as our data. RMSE measures the average difference between the values predicted by our model, and the actual values in our data that was not used to build our model (in our test or validation set). We can see below that on average, the SLR model predicted value for enrollment was 4,186,785 off from the actual enrollment value, while the MLR model prediction for enrollment was 3,617,640 off from the actual enrollment value. Again, these values for RMSE are high, but there was a very large amont of variation within our groups attempting to predict enrollment value, and most enrollment values were very large in themselves, so these large numbers are to be expected.

MLR Model RMSE is: 3617640
